snippet.textDisplay: Iron has a metallic atomic radius of 126 pm, meaning the width of an iron atom in a lump of iron is around 252 pm. Assuming the final billet is around 1 cm thick, and has 2 million layers, each layer is 0.000005 mm thick, or 5000 pm. 5000 pm divided by the width of an iron atom (252 pm) gives a number of just under 20 atoms per layer.

snippet.textDisplay: Alec, did you say you were going to have the blade weigh 11.5 lbs, or you need that much to have a sturdy enough blade by the end of the forging process? Because historical Flammenschwert Zweihanders, and battlefield Zweihanders in general come to that, weigh in at roughly 6-7 lbs total.

snippet.textDisplay: I've often wondered about recycling the waste you guys make (It always looked like an awful lot). The grinder dust may be too contaminated to recycle in a canister Damascus. But if gather the shavings from your lathe and mill as well as the cut dust from your band saw, you could recycle a lot of your shop waste into canister Damascus. Just a thought for, 1: Cost savings, 2: some potentially cool looking projects, and 3: some interesting videos. Maybe use a pan too catch the waste from mild steel to segregate it from the rest of the scrap, since mild steel is un-hardenable.
snippet.textOriginal: I've often wondered about recycling the waste you guys make (It always looked like an awful lot). The grinder dust may be too contaminated to recycle in a canister Damascus.
